guage=en|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n|2014\u201316||rowspan=1|[[Veolia Environmental Services|Veolia]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adelaideunited.com.au/news/adelaide-united-re-signs-veolia|title=Adelaide United re-signs with Veolia|website=Adelaide United|language=en|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref>\n|South Australia Tourism\n|-\n|2016\u201317|| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Macron (sportswear)|Macron]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adelaideunited.com.au/news/adelaide-united-announces-macron-partnership|title=Adelaide United announces Macron partnership|website=Adelaide United|language=en|access-date=2019-09-19}}</ref>||rowspan=2|[[IGA (Australian supermarket group)|IGA]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.borderchronicle.com.au/story/4086079/keith-iga-help-out-local-footy/|title=Keith IGA help out local footy|date=2016-08-12|website=Border Chronicle|language=en|access-date=2019-09-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160813133126/http://www.borderchronicle.com.au/story/4086079/keith-iga-help-out-local-footy/|archive-date=13 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| \u2013\n|Brand South Australia (2016)\n|-\n|2017\u201318\n|\u2013\n|AusGold Mining Group (2017)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sportspromedia.com/news/adelaide-united-secure-ausgold-as-afc-champions-league-sponsor|title=Adelaide United secure Ausgold as AFC Champions League sponsor \u2013 SportsPro Media|website=www.sportspromedia.com|access-date=2019-09-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328002409/http://www.sportspromedia.com/news/adelaide-united-secure-ausgold-as-afc-champions-league-sponsor|archive-date=28 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|2019\u2013\n|[[Flinders University]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adelaideunited.com.au/news/reds-announce-flinders-university-new-premier-partner|title=Reds announce Flinders University as new Premier Partner|website=Adelaide United|language=en|access-date=2019-10-10}}</ref>\n|Starfish Developments<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ministryofsport.com.au/adelaide-united-secures-multi-year-back-of-jersey-deal-with-starfish-developments/|title=Adelaide United Secures Multi-Year Back-Of-Jersey Deal With Starfish Developments|date=2019-09-05|website=Ministry of Sport|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190906134940/https://ministryofsport.com.au/adelaide-united-secures-multi-year-back-of-jersey-deal-with-starfish-developments/|archive-date=6 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|\n|}\n\n==Stadium==\n{{See also|Hindmarsh Stadium}}\n[[File:HindmarshStadium.JPG|180px|thumb|Hindmarsh Stadium, home ground of Adelaide United]]\nAdelaide United play their home matches at [[Hindmarsh Stadium]] with the exceptions being when they played two games a year at Adelaide Oval, one against interstate rivals Melbourne Victory and traditional rivals Sydney FC. Even though Adelaide lost the first of these two encounters 3\u20131, it was South Australia's largest Association Football crowd in history with 25,039 people filling the stands, many others were turned away at the gates.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/home/index.php?pid=st&cid=102882 |title=Sydney over-run Adelaide |access-date=20 October 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090111233039/http://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/home/index.php?pid=st&cid=102882 |archive-date=11 January 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The second match in 2009 saw 23,002 people attend the game.<ref name=\"adelaideovalmatch\">{{cite news\n |url=http://adelaideunited.com.au/default.aspx?s=newsdisplay&id=25855\n |title=Adelaide regains top spot with win over Sydney FC\n |publisher=Adelaide United\n |date=3 January 2009\n |accessdate=4 January 2009\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110414165744/http://www.adelaideunited.com.au/default.aspx?s=newsdisplay&id=25855\n |archivedate=14 April 2011\n |df=dmy\n}}</ref>\n\nHindmarsh Stadium [[seating capacity]] is 17,000. Adelaide United's first home game in the now-defunct [[National Soccer League]] saw over 15,000 supporters watch Adelaide win 1\u20130 over the [[Brisbane Strikers FC|Brisbane Strikers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/10/19/1066502072784.html?from=storyrhs |title=Reformed Adelaide reap the rewards of a United front |access-date=20 October 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081030024422/http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/10/19/1066502072784.html?from=storyrhs |archive-date=30 October 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA-League crowds have averaged 10,947 in [[2005\u201306 A-League|2005\u201306]] and over 12,000 supporters attending in both [[2006\u201307 A-League|2006\u201307]] and [[2007\u201308 A-League|2007\u201308]] seasons. Even with a lack of on-field success, crowds at United's games remained healthy during the [[2009\u201310 A-League|2009\u201310]] season relative to other clubs, largely due to the club's strong community-based initiatives.<ref>[http://www.theroar.com.au/2010/01/29/why-are-bottom-club-adelaides-crowds-so-good/ Why are bottom-club Adelaide's crowds so good?] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100203022043/http://www.theroar.com.au/2010/01/29/why-are-bottom-club-adelaides-crowds-so-good/ |date=3 February 2010 }}, The Roar, Retrieved on 1 February 2010.</ref> The record attendance for Hindmarsh Stadium was a full house of 17,000 on 12 November 2008 against Gamba Osaka in the historic second leg of the ACL final.<ref>[http://adelaideunited.com.au/default.aspx?s=newsdisplay&id=24819 Gamba Osaka too good for Adelaide in ACL Final] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110414182948/http://www.adelaideunited.com.au/default.aspx?s=newsdisplay&id=24819 |date=14 April 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Support==\n[[File:Adelaide United Fans (395036058).jpg|thumb|right|292px|Adelaide United supporters at the [[2007 A-League Grand Final]]]]\nAdelaide United's main active [[supporters' group]] is called the Red Army.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Migliaccio|first1=Val|title=Red Army wants Victorian police to assure its safety at AAMI Park when United plays Victory|url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/sport/football/a-league/teams/adelaide/red-army-writes-to-victorian-police-asking-for-protection-at-aami-park-when-united-plays-victory/news-story/122a73e593ac737c1cfd409ca21b53a7|website=The Advertiser|publisher=News Corporation|accessdate=21 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Migliaccio|first1=Val|title=Red Army setting \u2018fine example\u2019 as stadium officials say Vic fans\u2019 rampage won\u2019t be repeated in Adelaide|url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/sport/football/a-league/teams/adelaide/red-army-setting-fine-example-as-stadium-officials-say-vic-fans-rampage-wont-be-repeated-in-adelaide/news-story/6e1f326bbec59eda1202f9f5a6b6a96c|website=The Advertiser|publisher=News Corporation|accessdate=21 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160220053233/http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/sport/football/a-league/teams/adelaide/red-army-setting-fine-example-as-stadium-officials-say-vic-fans-rampage-wont-be-repeated-in-adelaide/news-story/6e1f326bbec59eda1202f9f5a6b6a96c|archive-date=20 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Rivalries==\nAdelaide United's  rivals are [[Melbourne Victory FC|Melbourne Victory]]. Adelaide was again one of two of the leading teams in the [[2006\u201307 A-League|2006\u201307]] season this time against Melbourne that saw an altercation between John Kosmina, the Adelaide United manager, and [[Kevin Muscat]] after the Victory captain knocked Kosmina over after entering the technical area to retrieve a ball. Kosmina then jumped up and grabbed Muscat around the throat for a few seconds.<ref>[http://www.news.com.au/adelaidenow/story/0,22606,20594523-12428,00.html Kosmina faces ban for fracas]</ref> Season events culminated in the year's grandfinal that saw Adelaide captain, [[Ross Aloisi]], sent off and Melbourne winning 6\u20130. The rivalry went beyond extreme after Melbourne defeated Adelaide United 1\u20130 in the 2008\u201309 grand final with United imported striker, Cristiano, given a controversial straight [[Fouls and misconduct (association football)|red card]]. The rivalry then went even further when Adelaide United defeated Melbourne 4\u20131 at AAMI Park, after United had been suffering a record-breaking 10-game losing streak against the Victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=111904.html |title=A-League toasts magical Melbourne |access-date=19 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150109085357/http://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=111904.html |archive-date=9 January 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Affiliated clubs==\n\n*{{flagicon|China}} [[Qingdao Red Lions F.C.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com.au/football/adelaide-united/story/3409725/adelaide-united-sold-to-netherlands-based-european-consortium|title=Adelaide United sold to Netherlands-based European consortium|date=7 March 2018|access-date=7 June 2019|publisher=espn.com.au|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190607021047/https://www.espn.com.au/football/adelaide-united/story/3409725/adelaide-united-sold-to-netherlands-based-european-consortium|archive-date=7 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics and records==\n{{details|List of Adelaide United FC records and statistics}}\n[[File:BruceDjite.JPG|thumb|upright=0.7|[[Bruce Djite]] is Adelaide United's record goalscorer, with 44 goals in all competitions.]]\n\nAdelaide United are the only team with a single championship in the [[A-League]] along with the [[Newcastle Jets FC|Newcastle Jets]]. They hold the highest number of [[FFA Cup]] trophies, with 3.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theffacup.com.au/news/live-adelaide-united-v-melbourne-city|title=Adelaide United rout Melbourne City 4-0 for third FFA Cup win|last=Windon|first=Jacob|date=24 October 2019|publisher=[[Football Federation Australia]]|website=[[FFA Cup]]}}</ref>. The club is the only team to have won the FFA Cup twice in succesion, in 2018 and 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rsssf.com/tablesa/auschamp.html|title=Australia \u2014 List of Champions|publisher=Rec.Sports.Soccer Statistics Foundation|last=Esamie|first=Thomas|accessdate=17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe club has only been in one [[AFC Champions League]] Final along with the [[Western Sydney Wanderers FC|Western Sydney Wanderers]]. The Final's result had Adelaide losing in a 5\u20130 loss with both legs having them be defeated by [[Gamba Osaka]] 3\u20130 and 2\u20130.\n\n[[Eugene Galekovic]] holds the record for Adelaide United appearances, having played 285 first-team matches between 2007 and 2017. Followed by centre-back [[Michael Marrone (soccer)|Michael Marrone]] comes second, having played 185 times. [[Bruce Djite]] is the club's top goalscorer with 44 goals in all competitions from two spells from 2006 to 2008 and 2011 to 2016.\n\nAdelaide United's record home attendance is 50,119, for an [[A-League]] Grand Final match against the [[Western Sydney Wanderers FC|Western Sydney Wanderers]] on 1 May 2016 at [[Adelaide Oval]], where the club played it's matches at reserved grounds. The record attendance for an Adleaide United match at [[Hindmarsh]] is 25,039 for a 1\u20133 loss against [[Sydney FC]] on 28 December 2007.\n\n==Players==\n{{See also|List of Adelaide United FC players|List of Adelaide United club award winners}}\n\n===First team squad===\n{{updated|30 January 2020}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adelaideunited.com.au/teams|title=Adelaide United squad|publisher=Adelaide United|access-date=20 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619214313/https://www.adelaideunited.com.au/teams|archive-date=19 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{about||recent transfers|2019\u201320 Adelaide United FC season#Transfers}}\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player |no=2  |pos=DF |nat=AUS |name=[[Michael Marrone (footballer)|Michael Marrone]]}}\n{{Fs