ead Coach of the Kansas City Chiefs 2012, Cleveland Browns 2005\u20132008\n*[[Joe Bugel]] \u2013 Former Head Coach of the Oakland Raiders 1997\n*[[Willie Taggart]] \u2013 Former Head Coach of the Florida State University Seminoles, former [[Oregon Ducks football|Oregon Ducks]] Head Coach, and former WKU Head Coach from 2010 to 2012, and played QB from 1995 to 1998\n*[[Eagle Keys|Eagle \"Buddy\" Keys]] \u2013 Former Head Coach in the [[Canadian Football League|CFL]], [[Grey Cup]] Champion, member of the [[Canadian Football Hall of Fame]]\n*[[Rod Smart]] \u2013 former running back for the [[Carolina Panthers]] and [[Las Vegas Outlaws (XFL)]]. More famously known by the nickname \"He Hate Me\".\n*[[Jason Michael]] \u2013 QB of 2002 National Championship team, Current Offensive Coordinator for [[Tennessee Titans]]\n*[[Brandon Doughty]]  \u2013 2014 Sammy Baugh Award Winner and all-time passing leader at WKU\n*[[George Fant]] \u2013 Former [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers basketball]] star and current offensive tackle for the [[Seattle Seahawks]]\n\n== Notable Hilltopper coaches ==\n\n=== Head coaches ===\n\n* L.T. Smith (1920\u20131921, Head Coach) \u2013 Namesake of [[L.T. Smith Stadium]]\n* [[Edgar Diddle|E.A. Diddle]] (1922\u20131928, Head Coach) \u2013 Legendary [[WKU Hilltoppers basketball]] Head Coach, symbol behind for WKU's red towel logo, and namesake of [[E. A. Diddle Arena]]\n* Nick Denes (1957\u20131967, Head Coach) \u2013 Namesake of [[Nick Denes Field]]\n* [[Jimmy Feix]] (1968\u20131983, Head Coach; 1957\u20131967, Assistant Coach; 1986\u20131991, Athletic Director) \u2013 Winningest coach in WKU history; 1973, 1978, and 1980 Ohio Valley Conference Coach of the Year; 1973 and 1975 NCAA Division II National Runners-up, and namesake of Feix Field in L.T. Smith Stadium.\n* [[Jack Harbaugh]] (1989\u20132002, Head Coach) \u2013 2000 Ohio Valley Conference Coach of the Year, 2002 [[AFCA Coach of the Year]] (FCS), 2002 FCS National Champion\n* [[Bobby Petrino]] (2013) \u2013 Former coach at University of Louisville, University of Arkansas, and the NFL's Atlanta Falcons spent 13 months as head coach at WKU before returning to Louisville in January 2014\n\n=== Assistants ===\n\n* [[Tommy Prothro]] (1942, Assistant Coach) \u2013 Former Head Coach \u2013 [[Oregon State]] and [[UCLA]], Former Head Coach \u2013 [[Los Angeles Rams]] and [[San Diego Chargers]], member of the [[College Football Hall of Fame]]\n* [[Jerry Glanville]] (1967, Defensive Coordinator) \u2013 Former Head Coach of the Houston Oilers and the [[Atlanta Falcons]]\n* [[Jim Harbaugh]] (1994\u20132001, Assistant Coach) \u2013 Former [[National Football League|NFL]] Head Coach for the [[San Francisco 49ers]] and current Head Coach at the [[University of Michigan]], was a certified, unpaid assistant under his father while playing in the NFL\n* [[Don Martindale]] \u2013 (2001\u201303, LB Coach, Defensive Coordinator) Current Linebackers coach for the [[Baltimore Ravens]]\n\n==Retired jerseys==\nWestern Kentucky has retired four jersey numbers.<ref name=\"2017MG\" />{{RP|143}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Western Kentucky Hilltoppers|No.|Name|Years|Retired}}\n|-\n| '''1''' || [[Willie Taggart]] || 1995\u20131998 || 1999\n|-\n| '''24''' || [[Virgil Livers]] || 1971\u20131974 || 2001\n|-\n| '''44''' || [[Dale Lindsey]] || 1963\u20131964 || 2007\n|-\n| '''66''' || [[Jimmy Feix]] || 1949\u20131952 || 1999\n|}\n\n==Individual award winners==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Award<ref>[https://wkusports.com/documents/2019/7/17/2019_WKU_Football_Media_Guide.pdf WKU Football Media Guide retrieved 31 March 2020.]</ref>\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Name\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Year(s)\n|-\n|[[Ohio Valley Conference]] Coach of the Year\n|Nick Denes\n[[Jimmy Feix]]\n\n[[Jack Harbaugh]]\n|1963\n1973, 1978, 1980\n\n2000\n|-\n|Division I-AA [[AFCA Coach of the Year]]\n|[[Jack Harbaugh]]\n|2002\n|-\n|[[Gateway Football Conference]] Freshman of the Year\n|Justin Haddix\n|2003\n|-\n|[[Sun Belt Conference]] Player of the Year\n|[[Antonio Andrews]]\n|2013\n|-\n|[[Sun Belt Conference]] Offensive Player of the Year\n|[[Bobby Rainey]]\n[[Antonio Andrews]]\n|2010, 2011\n2013\n|-\n|[[Sun Belt Conference]] Defensive Player of the Year\n|[[Quanterus Smith]]\nXavius Boyd\n|2012\n2013\n|-\n|[[Sammy Baugh Trophy]] Award Winner\n|[[Brandon Doughty]]\n|2014\n|-\n|[[Conference USA]] Most Valuable Player\n|[[Brandon Doughty]]\n|2014, 2015\n|-\n|[[Conference USA]] Defensive Player of the Year\n|DeAngelo Malone\n|2019\n|-\n|[[Conference USA]] Newcomer of the Year\n|Ty Storey\n|2019\n|-\n|[[Conference USA]] Coach of the Year\n|[[Tyson Helton]]\n|2019\n|}\n\n==All-Americans==\nFive players have been designated by the NCAA as \"Consensus All-Americans\" as of 2017.<ref name=\"2017MG\" />{{RP|137}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Western Kentucky Hilltoppers|Player|Position|Year}}\n|-\n| James Edwards || [[Free safety|FS]] || 1987\n|-\n| [[Bobby Sippio]] || [[Cornerback|CB]] || 2000\n|-\n| [[Mel Mitchell]] || [[Safety (gridiron football position)|S]] || 2001\n|-\n| Chris Price || [[Guard (American football)|G]] || 2002\n|-\n| Buster Ashley || [[Tackle (gridiron football position)|T]] || 2004\n|}\n\n==Rivalries==\nWKU has several historic rivalries that stem from its time in the [[Ohio Valley Conference]]. Since WKU's transition to the [[Football Bowl Subdivision]] in 2007, two of these rivalry games are no longer played on an annual basis.\n\n===Middle Tennessee State===\n{{Main|100 Miles of Hate}}\n[[Middle Tennessee\u2013Western Kentucky football rivalry|100 Miles of Hate]] is the name of the long-standing rivalry with [[Middle Tennessee State Blue Raiders football|Middle Tennessee]]. As WKU's oldest rivalry the two programs played together for several decades in the [[Ohio Valley Conference]] before both became members of the [[Sun Belt Conference]] and then transitioned to [[Conference USA]] about the same time. The name comes from the fact that the two universities are separated by about 100 miles.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Games played\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |First meeting\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Last meeting\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Win streak\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Wins\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Losses\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Ties\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Win %\n|-\n|67\n|1914, MTSU 47\u20130\n|2018, MTSU 29\u201310\n|3, WKU (2015\u20132017)\n|32\n|34\n|1\n|.492\n|}\n\n===Eastern Kentucky===\n{{Main|Battle of the Bluegrass}}\nWKY's has an inactive rivalry with [[Eastern Kentucky Colonels football|Eastern Kentucky]]. The two programs have met 84 times in football since 1914. The rivalry has taken a hiatus since leaving EKU behind as WKU transitioned to FBS in 2009. The programs scheduled a one-game match-up in 2017 in which WKU won 31\u201317 in Bowling Green, KY.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Games played\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |First meeting\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Last meeting\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Win streak\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Wins\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Losses\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Ties\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Win %\n|-\n|85\n|1914, EKU 34\u20136\n|2017, WKU 37\u201313\n|3, WKU (2007\u20132017)\n|47\n|35\n|3\n|.571\n|}\n\n===Murray State===\n{{Main|Battle for the Red Belt}}\nWKU has an inactive rivalry with nearby [[Murray State Racers football|Murray State]]. The two programs have met 67 times since the rivalry began in 1931. The Red Belt trophy was introduced to the rivalry series in 1978 when Murray's athletic trainer failed to pack a belt for the Racers' road trip and was loaned one by legendary WKU athletic trainer Bill \"Doc E\" Edwards.<ref>[http://www.wkusports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=5400&ATCLID=1584257] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302221804/http://www.wkusports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=5400&ATCLID=1584257|date=March 2, 2012}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Games played\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |First meeting\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Last meeting\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Win streak\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Wins\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Losses\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Ties\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Win %\n|-\n|67\n|1931, WKU 7\u20130\n|2008, WKU 50\u20139\n|4, WKU (1999\u20132008)\n|36\n|24\n|7\n|.589\n|}\n\n==Future non-conference opponents==\nAnnounced schedules as of January 27, 2020.<ref name=\"nonconfopp\">{{cite web|title=Western Kentucky Hilltoppers Football Future Schedules|publisher=FBSchedules.com|url=https://fbschedules.com/ncaa/wku/|accessdate=January 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Western Kentucky Hilltoppers|2020|2021|2022|2023|2024|2025|2026|2027|2028}}\n|-\n| [[Chattanooga Mocs football|Chattanooga]]\n| [[UT Martin Skyhawks football|UT Martin]]\n| [[Austin Peay Governors football|Austin Peay]]\n| [[South Florida Bulls football|South Florida]] \n| at [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]]\n| at [[Liberty Flames football|Liberty]]\n| at [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]]\n| at [[Ball State Cardinals football|Ball State]]\n| at [[Miami Redhawks football|Miami (OH)]]\n|- \n| at [[Indiana Hoosiers football|Indiana]]\n| at [[Army Black Knights football|Army]]\n| at [[Hawaii Warriors football|Hawaii]]\n| [[Houston Baptist Huskies football|Houston Baptist]]\n| [[Eastern Kentucky Colonels football|Eastern Kentucky]]\n| at [[Toledo Rockets football|Toledo]]\n| [[Ball State Cardinals football|Ball State]]\n| [[Miami Redhawks football|Miami (OH)]]\n| \n|-\n| [[Liberty Flames football|Liberty]]\n| [[Indiana Hoosiers football|Indiana]]\n| at [[Indiana Hoosiers football|Indiana]]\n| at [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]]\n| [[Toledo Rockets football|Toledo]]\n| [[Cincinnati Bearcats football|Cincinnati]]\n| at [[Cincinnati Bearcats football|Cincinnati]]\n| \n| \n|-\n| at [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]]\n| at [[Michigan State Spartans football|Michigan State]]\n| [[Troy Trojans football|Troy]]\n| at [[Troy Trojans football|Troy]]\n| at [[South Florida Bulls football|South Florida]]\n| \n| \n| \n| \n|-\n| \n| \n| at [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]]\n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{WKU Hilltoppers football navbox}}\n{{Western Kentucky University}}\n{{Conference USA football navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football|*]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs established in 1908]]\n[[Category:1908 establishments in Kentucky]]\n", "name_user": "MHS1976", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eJeff Brohm (2014\u20132016):Added links to team pages", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_Kentucky_Hilltoppers_football"}
{"title_page": "MES (buffer)", "text_new": "{{Chembox\n| Verifiedfields = changed\n| Watchedfields = changed\n| verifiedrevid = 424810828\n| ImageFile = MES.svg\n| ImageSize = 250px\n| Name = MES\n| IUPACName = 2-morpholin-4-ylethanesulfonic acid <br> Zwitterion: 2-morpholin-4-ium-4-ylethanesulfonate\n| OtherNames =2-(''N''-morpholino)ethanesulfonic acid \n|Section1={{Chembox Identifiers\n| CASNo_Ref = {{cascite|correct|??}}\n| RTECS = \n| EINECS = \n| CASNo = 4432-31-9\n| PubChem = 78165\n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|changed|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID = 70541\n| ChEBI_Ref = {{ebicite|changed|EBI}} \n| ChEBI = 39005\n| SMILES = C1COCCN1CCS(=O)(=O)O\n| InChI = 1/C6H13NO4S/c8-12(9,10)6-3-7-1-4-11-5-2-7/h1-6H2,(H,8,9,10)\n| InChIKey = SXGZJKUKBWWHRA-UHFFFAOYAP\n| StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|changed|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI = 1S/C6H13NO4S/c8-12(9,10)6-3-7-1-4-11-5-2-7/h1-6H2,(H,8,9,10)\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|changed|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = SXGZJKUKBWWHRA-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n }}\n|Section2={{Chembox Properties\n| Formula = C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>13</sub>NO<sub>4</sub>S\n| MolarMass = 195.2 g/mol\n| Appearance = \n| Density = \n| MeltingPt = \n| BoilingPt = \n| Solubility = \n }}\n|Section3={{Chembox Hazards\n| MainHazards = \n| FlashPt = \n| AutoignitionPt =\n }}\n}}\n'''MES''' is the common name for the compound '''2-(''N''-morpholino)ethanesulfonic acid'''. Its chemical structure contains a [[morpholine]] ring. It has a [[molecular weight]] of 195.2 and the [[chemical formula]] is C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>13</sub>NO<sub>4</sub>S. Synonyms include: 2-morpholinoethanesulfonic acid; 2-(4-morpholino)ethanesulfonic acid; 2-(N-morpholino)ethanesulfonic acid; 2-(4-morpholino)ethanesulfonic acid; MES; MES hydrate; and morpholine-4-ethanesulfonic acid hydrate. [[MOPS]] is a similar pH buffering compound which contains a propanesulfonic [[Moiety (chemistry)|moiety]] instead of an ethanesulfonic one.\n\n==Applications==\nMES is used as a [[buffering agent]] in [[biology]] and [[biochemistry]]. It has [[pKa|p''K''<sub>a</sub>]] value of 6.15 at 20&nbsp;\u00b0C. The pH (and pKa at [[ionic strength]] I\u22600) of the buffer solution changes with concentration and temperature, and this effect may be predicted using online calculators.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Biological buffers |url=http://www.reachdevices.com/Protein/BiologicalBuffers.html |publisher=REACH Devices}}</ref> MES is highly soluble in water. The [[melting point]] is approx. 300&nbsp;\u00b0C.\n\nMES was developed as one of [[Good's buffers]] in the 1960s. These buffers were developed with the following criteria in mind: midrange p''K''<sub>a</sub>, maximum water [[solubility]] and minimum solubility in all other [[solvents]], minimal salt effects, minimal change in p''K''<sub>a</sub> with temperature, chemically and enzymatically stable, minimal [[absorption (chemistry)|absorption]] in visible or [[Ultraviolet|UV]] spectral range and reasonably easily synthesized.<ref name=\"Good\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1021/bi00866a011|title=Hydrogen Ion Buffers for Biological Research|pmid=5942950|year=1966|last1=Good|first1=Norman E.|last2=Winget|first2=G. Douglas|last3=Winter|first3=Wilhelmina|last4=Connolly|first4=Thomas N.|last5=Izawa|first5=Seikichi|last6=Singh|first6=Raizada M. M.|journal=Biochemistry|volume=5|issue=2|pages=467\u201377}}</ref> MES is also useful as a non-coordinating buffer in chemistry involving metal ions, as many common buffers (e.g. [[phosphate]] and [[acetate]]) readily form [[coordination complexes]]. MES only weakly binds Ca, Mg, Mn, and it has negligible binding with Cu(II).\n<ref name=\"Good\" />\n<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kandegedara|first1=A.|last2=Rorabacher|first2=D. B.|journal=Anal. Chem.|year=1999|volume=71|pages=3140\u20133144|doi= 10.1021/ac9902594|title=Noncomplexing Tertiary Amines as \"Better\" Buffers Covering the Range of pH 3\u221211. Temperature Dependence of Their Acid Dissociation Constants|pmid=21662904}}</ref>\n\n==Safety==\n\nContact with this buffer is hazardous;<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sciencelab.com/msds.php?msdsId=9924627 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-09-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920161745/http://www.sciencelab.com/msds.php?msdsId=9924627 |archive-date=2018-09-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[human skin|skin]] or [[human eye|eye]] exposure should be cleaned well with water and medical aid should be sought in the case of eye exposure, swallowing or [[inhalation]] of dust. It also emits [[toxic]] fumes upon combustion, including [[carbon monoxide]], [[nitrogen oxide]] and [[sulfur oxide]]s.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[CAPSO]]\n*[[CHES (buffer)|CHES]]\n*[[MOPS]]\n*[[HEPES]]\n*[[HEPPS (molecule)|HEPPS]]\n*[[Tris]]\n*[[Buffer solution#Common buffer compounds used in biology|Common buffer compounds used in biology]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://openwetware.org/wiki/MES MES on OpenWetWare]\n\n[[Category:Buffers]]\n[[Category:Sulfonic acids]]\n[[Category:Morpholines]]\n", "text_old": "{{Chembox\n| Verifiedfields = changed\n| Watchedfields = changed\n| verifiedrevid = 424810828\n| ImageFile = MES.svg\n| ImageSize = 250px\n| Name = MES\n| IUPACName = 2-morpholin-4-ylethanesulfonic acid <br> Zwitterion: 2-morpholin-4-ium-4-ylethanesulfonate\n| OtherNames =2-(''N''-morpholino)ethanesulfonic acid \n|Section1={{Chembox Identifiers\n| CASNo_Ref = {{cascite|correct|??}}\n| RTECS = \n| EINECS = \n| CASNo = 4432-31-9\n| PubChem = 78165\n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|changed|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID = 70541\n| ChEBI_Ref = {{ebicite|changed|EBI}} \n| ChEBI = 39005\n| SMILES = C1COCCN1CCS(=O)(=O)O\n| InChI = 1/C6H13NO4S/c8-12(9,10)6-3-7-1-4-11-5-2-7/h1-6H2,(H,8,9,10)\n| InChIKey = SXGZJKUKBWWHRA-UHFFFAOYAP\n| StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|changed|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI = 1S/C6H13NO4S/c8-12(9,10)6-3-7-1-4-11-5-2-7/h1-6H2,(H,8,9,10)\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|changed|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = SXGZJKUKBWWHRA-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n }}\n|Section2={{Chembox Properties\n| Formula = C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>13</sub>NO<sub>4</sub>S\n| MolarMass = 195.2 g/mol\n| Appearance = \n| Density = \n| MeltingPt = \n| BoilingPt = \n| Solubility = \n }}\n|Section3={{Chembox Hazards\n| MainHazards = \n| FlashPt = \n| AutoignitionPt =\n }}\n}}\n'''MES''' is the common name for the compound '''2-(''N''-morpholino)ethanesulfonic acid'''. Its chemical structure contains a [[morpholine]] ring. It has a [[molecular weight]] of 195.2 and the [[chemical formula]] is C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>13</sub>NO<sub>4</sub>S. Synonyms include: 2-morpholinoethanesulfonic acid; 2-(4-morpholino)ethanesulfonic acid; 2-(N-morpholino)ethanesulfonic acid; 2-(4-morpholino)ethanesulfonic acid; MES; MES hydrate; and morpholine-4-ethanesulfonic acid hydrate. [[MOPS]] is a similar pH buffering compound which contains a propanesulfonic [[Moiety (chemistry)|moiety]] instead of an ethanesulfonic one.\n\n==Applications==\nMES is used as a [[buffering agent]] in [[biology]] and [[biochemistry]]. It has [[pKa|p''K''<sub>a</sub>]] value of 6.15 at 20&nbsp;\u00b0C. The pH (and pKa at [[ionic strength]] I\u22600) of the buffer solution changes with concentration and temperature, and this effect may be predicted using online calculators.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Biological buffers |url=http://www.reachdevices.com/Protein/BiologicalBuffers.html |publisher=REACH Devices}}</ref> MES is highly soluble in water. The [[melting point]] is approx. 300&nbsp;\u00b0C.\n\nMES was developed as one of [[Good's buffers]] in the 1960s. These buffers were developed with the following criteria in mind: midrange p''K''<sub>a</sub>, maximum water [[solubility]] and minimum solubility in all other [[solvents]], minimal salt effects, minimal change in p''K''<sub>a</sub> with temperature, chemically and enzymatically stable, minimal [[absorption (chemistry)|absorption]] in visible or [[Ultraviolet|UV]] spectral range and reasonably easily synthesized.<ref name=\"Good\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1021/bi00866a011|title=Hydrogen Ion Buffers for Biological Research|pmid=5942950|year=1966|last1=Good|first1=Norman E.|last2=Winget|first2=G. Douglas|last3=Winter|first3=Wilhelmina|last4=Connolly|first4=Thomas N.|last5=Izawa|first5=Seikichi|last6=Singh|first6=Raizada M. M.|journal=Biochemistry|volume=5|issue=2|pages=467\u201377}}</ref> MES is also useful as a non-coordinating buffer in chemistry involving metal ions, as many common buffers (e.g. [[phosphate]] and [[acetate]]) readily form [[coordination complexes]]. MES only weakly binds Ca, Mg, Mn, and it has negligible binding with Cu(II).\n<ref name=\"Good\" />\n<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kandegedara|first1=A.|last2=Rorabacher|first2=D. B.|journal=Anal. Chem.|year=1999|volume=71|pages=3140\u20133144|doi= 10.1021/ac9902594|title=Noncomplexing Tertiary Amines as \"Better\" Buffers Covering the Range of pH 3\u221211. Temperature Dependence of Their Acid Dissociation Constants|pmid=21662904}}</ref>\n\n==Safety==\n\nContact with this buffer is hazardous;<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sciencelab.com/msds.php?msdsId=9924627 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-09-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920161745/http://www.sciencelab.com/msds.php?msdsId=9924627 |archive-date=2018-09-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[human skin|skin]] or [[human eye|eye]] exposure should be cleaned well with water and medical aid should be sought in the case of eye exposure, swallowing or [[inhalation]] of dust. It also emits [[toxic]] fumes upon combustion, including [[carbon monoxide]], [[nitrogen oxide]] and [[sulfur oxide]]s.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[CAPSO]]\n*[[CHES (buffer)|CHES]]\n*[[MOPS]]\n*[[HEPES]]\n*[[HEPPS (molecule)|HEPPS]]\n*[[Tris]]\n*[[Buffer solution#Common buffer compounds used in biology|Common buffer compounds used in biology]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n[[Category:Buffers]]\n[[Category:Sulfonic acids]]\n[[Category:Morpholines]]\n", "name_user": "Photocyte", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MES_(buffer)"}
